titleInfo.title: USA v. Jaynes
titleInfo.subTitle: ORDER granting 20 Oral Motion. IT IS ORDERED: 1. Jaynes's motion to continue trial is granted. 2. Trial of this matter is re-scheduled for September 8, 2008, before Chief Judge Joseph F. Bataillon and a jury. The ends of justice have been served by granting such motion and outweigh the interests of the public and the defendant in a speedy trial. The additional time arising as a result of the granting of the motion, i.e., the time betweenJuly 21, 2008 and September 8, 2008, shall be deemed excludable time in anycomputation of time under the requirement of the Speedy Trial Act for the reason that defendants counsel requires additional time to adequately prepare the case. The failure to grant additional time might result in a miscarriage of justice. 18 U.S.C. ยง 3161(h)(8)(A)&(B) as to Deanna M. Jaynes. Ordered by Magistrate Judge Thomas D. Thalken. ( PCV, )

titleInfo.title: USA v. Jaynes
titleInfo.subTitle: JUDGMENT as to Deanna M. Jaynes (1), Counts 1 and 3 - Defendant pleaded guilty to counts I and III of the Indictment and is committed to the custody of the United States Bureau of Prisons to be imprisoned for a term of forty-eight (48) months on count I and forty-eight (48) months on count III to be served concurrently; supervised release for a term of three (3) years on count I and three (3) years on count III to be run concurrently; $200.00 special assessment has been paid in full; The defendant shall surrender for service of sentence at the institution designated by the Bureau of Prisons as notified by the United States Marshal; Count 2 - Count II of the Indictment is dismissed on the motion of the United States as to this defendant onlyas to defendant(s) Deanna M. Jaynes. Ordered by Chief Judge Joseph F. Bataillon. (4 Certified copies to USM)(ADB, ) Modified on 1/15/2009 to add self surrender information (ADB, ).
